  "title": "Force and Energy stored in capacitor",
  "concepts": [
    {
      "title": "Force Between Plates of Capacitors",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Force between the plates of a capacitor&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>Electric field due to a single plate $=\\left( \\frac{\\sigma }{2{{\\epsilon }_{0}}} \\right)$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ Force }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ on }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ each }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ plate }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }=\\left( \\frac{\\text{Q}\\cdot \\text{Q}}{2{{\\in }_{0}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ A}} \\right)=\\frac{{{\\text{Q}}^{2}}}{2{{\\in }_{0}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ A}}$</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db1fc03b9dcaf1afe039"
    },
    {
      "title": "Potential Energy Stored in Capacitors",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Potential Energy stored in the Capacitor&nbsp;</strong></h3><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"91\" height=\"190\"></p><p>Electrostatic potential energy is stored in the capacitor is the form of the electric field</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{W}}_{\\text{ex}}}=\\text{F}\\left( \\text{d} \\right)$</p><p>$=\\frac{{{\\text{Q}}^{2}}}{\\left( 2{{\\in }_{0}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ A} \\right)}\\times \\text{d}=\\left( \\frac{1}{2}\\frac{{{\\text{Q}}^{2}}}{\\text{C}} \\right)$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ Potential energy stored in the capacitor $=\\frac{1}{2}\\frac{{{\\text{Q}}^{2}}}{\\text{C}}=\\frac{1}{2}\\text{C}{{\\text{V}}^{2}}=\\frac{1}{2}\\text{QV}$</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"104\" height=\"218\"></p><ul><li>When the capacitor is connected with a cell use $\\frac{1}{2}\\text{C}{{\\text{V}}^{2}}$</li><li>When the charge on the capacitor is constant, use $\\left( \\frac{1}{2}\\frac{{{Q}^{2}}}{C} \\right)$</li><li>When distance between the plates is increased $\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{W}}_{\\text{ex}}}=\\frac{1}{2}\\frac{{{\\text{Q}}^{2}}}{{{\\in }_{0}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ A}}\\left( \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{d}}_{2}}-{{\\text{d}}_{1}} \\right)$</li></ul>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db1fc03b9dcaf1afe03a"
    },
    {
      "title": "Energy Density Between Plates of Capacitors",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Energy density between the Capacitor Plates&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>Energy density = potential energy stored per unit volume</p><p>$\\begin{matrix} =\\left( \\frac{\\text{U}}{\\text{Ad}} \\right)=\\frac{1}{2}\\frac{{{\\text{Q}}^{2}}\\text{ d}}{\\left( {{\\in }_{0}}\\text{ A} \\right)\\text{Ad}}=\\frac{1}{2}\\frac{{{\\text{Q}}^{2}}}{{{\\in }_{0}}{{\\text{A}}^{2}}} \\\\ \\therefore \\text{ Energy }\\text{ density }=\\frac{1}{2}{{\\in }_{0}}{{\\text{E}}^{2}} \\\\ \\end{matrix}$</p><p>Although, we have derived the expression for energy density in the capacitor, but is general this is valid for energy density is electric field, that is the energy stored per unit volume is the electric field.</p><p>$\\text{U}=\\frac{1}{2}{{\\in }_{0}}{{\\text{E}}^{2}}$</p><p>Using this we can calculate the self potential energy of a uniformly charged conducting sphere.</p><p>${{\\text{U}}_{0}}=\\mathop{\\int }_{\\text{R}}^{\\infty }\\frac{1}{2}{{\\epsilon }_{0}}{{\\text{E}}^{2}}\\text{dV}$</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"199\" height=\"197\"></p><p>$\\begin{array}{l} {{\\text{U}}_{0}} =\\mathop{\\int }_{\\text{R}}^{\\infty }\\frac{1}{2}{{\\epsilon }_{0}}{{\\left( \\frac{\\text{KQ}}{{{\\text{r}}^{2}}} \\right)}^{2}}\\left( 4\\pi {{\\text{r}}^{2}} \\right)\\text{dr} \\\\ =\\frac{1}{2}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{K}}^{2}}{{\\in }_{0}}{{\\text{Q}}^{2}}\\left( 2\\pi \\right)\\mathop{\\int }_{\\text{R}}^{\\infty }\\frac{1}{{{\\text{r}}^{2}}}\\text{dr} \\\\ =\\frac{1}{16{{\\pi }^{2}}{{\\in }_{0}}}{{\\text{Q}}^{2}}\\left( 2\\pi \\right)\\left| \\frac{-1}{\\text{r}} \\right|_{\\text{R}}^{\\infty }=\\left( \\frac{\\text{KQ}}{2\\text{R}} \\right) \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p><strong>For a non-conducting sphere&nbsp;</strong></p><p>\\(\\mathrm{U}_{\\mathrm{i}} \\neq 0, \\mathrm{U}_0=\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{KQ}^2}{2 \\mathrm{R}}\\right)\\)</p><p>$\\begin{array}{l} {{\\text{U}}_{\\text{i}}}=\\mathop{\\int }_{0}^{\\text{R}}\\frac{1}{2}{{\\in }_{0}}{{\\left( \\frac{\\rho \\text{r}}{3{{\\in }_{0}}} \\right)}^{2}}\\left( 4\\pi {{\\text{r}}^{2}} \\right)\\text{dr} \\\\ =\\frac{{{\\rho }^{2}}\\left( 4\\pi \\right)}{9\\times 2{{\\epsilon }_{0}}}\\times \\mathop{\\int }_{0}^{\\text{R}}{{\\text{r}}^{4}}\\text{dr} \\\\ \\text{ and } \\rho =\\left( \\frac{\\text{Q}}{\\frac{4}{3}\\pi {{\\text{R}}^{3}}} \\right) \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>\\(\\Rightarrow \\quad \\frac{9 \\mathrm{Q}^2(4 \\pi)}{(4 \\pi)^2 \\mathrm{R}^6 18 \\epsilon_0} \\times\\left(\\frac{\\mathrm{R}^5}{5}\\right)=\\frac{\\mathrm{KQ}^2}{10 \\mathrm{R}}\\)</p><p>$\\begin{array}{l} \\therefore {{\\text{U}}_{\\text{T}}}={{\\text{U}}_{0}}+{{\\text{U}}_{\\text{i}}}=\\left( \\frac{\\text{K}{{\\text{Q}}^{2}}}{2\\text{R}} \\right)+\\left( \\frac{\\text{K}{{\\text{Q}}^{2}}}{10\\text{R}} \\right)=\\left( \\frac{3\\text{K}{{\\text{Q}}^{2}}}{5\\text{R}} \\right) \\\\ \\end{array}$</p>",
      "position": 2,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db1fc03b9dcaf1afe03b"
    }
  ],
